  "doc_id": "19704",
  "text": "Sixth, contested exchange involves strategic behavior in personal interactions rather than the anonymous interaction and agreed-upon rights of Buchanan's roadside stand. In a world of contested exchange, it is often cost-reducing to forgo the flexibility of spot contracting and to secure long-term commitments from one's trading partners [CITATION_1] , so the identity of one's exchange partner matters. The paradigmatic form of economic action is not an agent intervening in a given external world, like the behavior of a price-taking firm or consumer, but rather an interaction among two or more agents, mutually aware of the reciprocal effects of their behavior. These durable exchange relationships have a face-to-face quality involving sufficiently few actors that the reciprocal effects of one's actions must be taken into account in selecting a strategy.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "154150790"
  },
